code chunk 1

Create a data frame comprised of:

A random sample of size 10 from a uniform[0, 5] distribution.

A logical vector indicating whether elements of the sample are greater than 2.

A (length-10) character vector.

A (length-10) factor vector.

library(tidyverse)
## -- Attaching packages ----------------------------------------------------- tidyverse 1.2.1 --
## <U+221A> ggplot2 3.0.0     <U+221A> purrr   0.2.5
## <U+221A> tibble  1.4.2     <U+221A> dplyr   0.7.6
## <U+221A> tidyr   0.8.1     <U+221A> stringr 1.3.1
## <U+221A> readr   1.1.1     <U+221A> forcats 0.3.0
## -- Conflicts -------------------------------------------------------- tidyverse_conflicts() --
## x dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
## x dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
dt_frame = tibble(
  random_sample = runif(10,0,5) ,
  logical_vector = random_sample > 2 ,
  ch_vector = c("a","b","c","d","e","f","g","h","i","j") ,
  factor_vector = as.factor(ch_vector) 
)
dt_frame = as.data.frame(dt_frame)
head(dt_frame)
##   random_sample logical_vector ch_vector factor_vector
## 1      4.925171           TRUE         a             a
## 2      3.244400           TRUE         b             b
## 3      4.234444           TRUE         c             c
## 4      1.596651          FALSE         d             d
## 5      3.374986           TRUE         e             e
## 6      3.849837           TRUE         f             f

The mean of each variable in the dataframe

The mean of random sample is 3.0409411

The mean of the logical vector is 0.9

The mean of the character vector is NA

The mean of the list of factor vector is NA

Explanation:The random sample and logical vector worked while character vector and factor vector didn`t work. According to the useage of mean(), the elements of the vector should be umeric/logical vectors and date, date-time and time interval objects.

code chunk 2

chr_to_num = as.numeric(dt_frame$ch_vector) 
chr_to_factor = as.factor(dt_frame$ch_vector) 

factor_to_chr = as.character(dt_frame$factor_vector) 
factor_to_num = as.numeric(dt_frame$factor_vector) 

logic_to_num = as.numeric(dt_frame$logical_vector)

Explanation：This shows the variables cannot be converted from character to numberic. Except that, some other kinds of conversions(factor to numberic to character,logic to numberic, character to factor ) can be realized successfully.

problem 2

code chunk 3

Create a data frame comprised of:

x: a random sample of size 1000 from a standard Normal distribution.

y: a random sample of size 1000 from a standard Normal distribution.

A logical vector indicating whether the x + y > 0.

A numeric vector created by coercing the above logical vector.

A factor vector created by coercing the above logical vector.

library(tidyverse)
dt_frame2 = tibble(
  x = rnorm(1000, mean = 0, sd = 1) , 
  y = rnorm(1000, mean = 0, sd = 1) ,
  vc_logic = x + y > 0 ,
  vc_num = as.numeric(vc_logic) ,
  vc_factor = as.factor(vc_logic)
)
dt_frame2 = as.data.frame(dt_frame2)
head(dt_frame2)
